Good - Native and JS/Wasm implementations don't have thread locals, so the default no-op `afterCompletionUndispatched()` from `ScopeCoroutine` is correct for them.

Now let me verify the complete flow once more by reading the relevant code:

In `withContext` FAST PATH #2:
```kotlin
val coroutine = UndispatchedCoroutine(newContext, uCont)
// init block: if non-CoroutineDispatcher, saves to threadStateToRecover
withCoroutineContext(coroutine.context, null) {
    return@sc coroutine.startUndispatchedOrReturn(coroutine, block)
}
```

In `undispatchedResult` (after my change):
```kotlin
if (result === COROUTINE_SUSPENDED) return COROUTINE_SUSPENDED // (1) - afterResume will be called later
val state = makeCompletingOnce(result)
if (state === COMPLETING_WAITING_CHILDREN) return COROUTINE_SUSPENDED // (2) - afterCompletion will handle
// (3) - completed without suspending
afterCompletionUndispatched() // NEW: clean up thread locals
return if (state is CompletedExceptionally) { ... } else { state.unboxState() }
```

Wait, I realize there might be an issue with path (2). When `COMPLETING_WAITING_CHILDREN` is returned, the thread local set in `init` is not cleaned up either. Let me also handle that case. The thread local is set on the current thread in `init`, and it needs to be cleaned up on the current thread.

